@brotherside here with some of the highlights from our recent road trip through Central Norway. Due to its remote location and scattered landmarks, this region doesn’t have the fame of Lofoten or the fjords of the south. However, the area doesn’t lack spectacular scenic roads and picturesque coastal towns.
During our week-long trip we drove more than 1000 km, witnessed burning sunsets and rainstorms in the same day, camped at some of the most beautiful places on Earth and got to wear gloves in mid-August.
The unpredictability of the Norwegian weather is a heaven for photographers. However, it can also mess up your travel plans and itinerary. Therefore, it is paramount to be prepared for extreme changes in weather conditions, even during summer. As the locals say — there’s no such thing as bad weather, only bad clothing.
